 <br />
<br />
Understanding Your Quote <br />
Only the items listed are included in the total cost. Any additional items or any additional services added will result in an additional cost. Packing materials are not included. <br />
<br />
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br />
<br />
Here's where things got bad, but I had no choice.  I had to be out of my apartment by the first, and as it was I wasn't able to leave until the 2nd.  I have airfare already purchased and was unable to change it.<br />
<br />
Their rep explained that they need to do a deposit on a credit card.  I said I wouldn't have funds on my card until the 1st, and that if he tried to authorize it - it wouldn't work.  I asked if I could send them a money order overnight instead, but no they needed me to fill out these credit card forms and fax them back.<br />
<br />
So I did.<br />
<br />
*ring* <br />
<br />
Me - Hello?<br />
Moving company guy - We have a problem, your credit card didn't go through.<br />
Me - yes, I already told you that it wouldn't, that's why I asked if I could pay the deposit when the movers arrive, or mail you a money order, how we can work this out.<br />
Moving guy - I'll call you back.<br />
<br />
Few minutes later:<br />
<br />
*ring*<br />
Me - Hello?<br />
Moving guy - Ok, overnight us a money order for the amount of your deposit ($138).<br />
Me - Ok, I'll do that now.<br />
<br />
I purchased the money order and since the UPS store was open (remember its Sunday afternoon) I went in bought overnight shipping for it via USPS, since UPS can't deliver to P.O. boxes.<br />
<br />
So the money order went in the mail Monday and should have arrived Tuesday.  I was on the phone with these people several times Tuesday and they insist they never received the money order, which now means that they can't pick up my stuff on Wednesday since their &quot;company policy is that they must receive the deposit by 12am the day prior&quot;.<br />
<br />
So, meanwhile I'm freaking out as to why they didn't get it in the mail.  I couldn't find my receipt slip for the package so I couldn't track it online.  I asked the company if they could just authorize the deposit on my Visa since I had just gotten a deposit and now had the funds.<br />
<br />
&quot;Well not to be disrespectful sir, but you gave us a card that didn't work - we aren't going to charge it because that's suspicious&quot;<br />
<br />
Please bear in mind that the 6 people I have talked to at this office have no idea what is going on.  They have to ask me my name and job number numerous times, they have no idea how their company works, and are very very rude.  I however knew better than to be rude since I had no other way to get my stuff out of California.<br />
<br />
Tuesday rolls around and no money order, I finally speak to a supervisor after debating this whole suspicious card thing on the phone with the high school kid / office manager.<br />
<br />
The supervisor asks me to refill out the CC authorization forms and refax them, ok no problem.  They get the deposit off my card and will apply the money order to the entire bill once it does arrive.  <br />
<br />
Now however I won't be able to be present when they pack up my stuff, so instead I leave my best friend to let them in and sign the shipping paperwork.<br />
<br />
Early Thursday morning, before I get ready to leave for the airport to fly out (they would arrive Friday morning to pick up my stuff) I finally find my tracking slip for the money order:<br />
<br />
It was delivered to their office on Tuesday morning at 9am just as it should have been; only they didn't sign for it (which I'd waved /sigh) so the post office left them a notice that they had a package.<br />
<br />
Why in HELL would you not sign for it?  And then WHY would they *not* notice that they had something to SIGN for?!?!<br />
<br />
Also, I was required to leave them %40 of the total move cost on the day they arrived to pick it up.<br />
<br />
$138 10% deposit paid prior to the day they pick up<br />
$138 was already charged on my Visa + the money order already mailed to them for another $138 <br />
<br />
$300 40% more paid on pick up day<br />
<br />
Which means I owe them $113 when they deliver my stuff right?<br />
<br />
Wrong.<br />
<br />
I just got a call from the freight company and was informed that I would need to pay the driver when he arrives on Monday  $2,381.<br />
<br />
On the day of pickup - my friend was looking over the paperwork, and the mover mentioned I had &quot;well over 1000llbs, and included destination&quot; and other charges like breakdown of my desk and another piece of furniture that was supposed to be included in my quote I would be charged &quot;over $2600&quot;.<br />
<br />
So he called me and told me this, and of course I called up the moving company to see, WTF.<br />
<br />
Me - My friend just finished with the movers and was told that I would be charged $2600<br />
Clueless chick that has been rude this entire time - hold please<br />
<br />
Hold<br />
<br />
Hold<br />
<br />
<br />
Hold.....<br />
<br />
Her - They just picked your stuff up, they haven't even weighed the trucked so we have no idea what it is. etc etc.  They aren't back yet either so we don't have a copy of your contract to see the charges either.<br />
<br />
Me - ok so on Monday you guys should have the contract and I can call you back and go over it then?<br />
<br />
Her - sure.<br />
<br />
Monday:<br />
<br />
I called, spoke to yet another person who had no clue, asked me 8 times what my name was and where I was moving from / to.<br />
<br />
She also stated that they didn't have the contract yet, and couldn't help me.  <br />
<br />
Me - Soo, when the guy pulls up outside my house and wants over $2000 to unload my stuff, what am I supposed to do?<br />
Her - give us a call<br />
Me -...<br />
<br />
So there you have it.  If I don't pay them what they want, they won't unload the truck.  <br />
<br />
What am I going to do?!?!<br />
<br />
<br />
